TRIP COMMENTS: While enjoying a nice quiet Sunday morning, I was alerted to the crows going crazy just outside my windows around 10am.  I walked down to the corner to find a juvenile Snowy Owl in the street surrounded by crows on the ground and above on all the wires and trees. Several neighbors enjoyed watching the owl for around 20 minutes.  It stayed put while one car came up the hill but the second car put the owl into flight and it headed north.  The crow escort dissipated and not sure exactly where it landed.  I walked around the neighborhood and was not able to re-locate the owl.
SPECIES COMMENTS: Large white owl with  heavy dark barring

TRIP COMMENTS: Many people coming and going on the street and sidewalk to get a look at Owl
SPECIES COMMENTS: Snowy Owl had killed a gull and pulled it from the sidewalk near some dumpsters. Lots of pedestrians were walking by and stopping to take pictures. Owl didn't seem to mind too much. Stayed there all night eating kill, was picked up in the next day by Sarvey Wildlife Care Center. She was underweight.------

I was alerted by crows. SNOW was perched 30 feet up in a fir tree being harassed by crows. It flew 2 blocks North and was harassed again and flew to a house roof on 17th and Republican. Flew again from their to the SW direction. Someone else got an iphone photo of it.

TRIP COMMENTS: - yay, the owl was still there!

LOCALITY: Sunset Hill Park King County Washington
TRIP COMMENTS: My granddaughter Gracey Wolverton was with me to see a Snowy Owl reported from this area on Tweeters.  We saw two.
SPECIES COMMENTS: We followed up on a Tweeters report and were able to find two of the owls from the edge of Sunset Hill Park.  One was on the roof of a gray house and the second one was in a Douglas Fir tree.  Both were seen from the edge of the park.  We went down to the bird that was in the tree at the corner of 34th Street and 70th Avenue.  Both of the birds looked like young birds with a fair amount of black feather edging on the back and belly.  Also black on the top of the head evident on the bird in the tree as it preened.  Also a vocalization like a little scream came from the bird in the tree.

According to other local neighborhood birders that one hadn't been seen for a few days.
